Boil a full #kettle{}. Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/2%tsp} on high heat.

Add the @spaghetti{180%g} and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{8%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

While the spaghetti cooks, drain the @king prawns{300%g}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the prawns. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and stir-fry for ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. They're cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{3}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Add the garlic to the prawns and fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @tomato passata{1%carton}, @red wine stock paste{28%g}, @mixed herbs{1%sachet}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{100%ml} for the sauce (see pantry for both amounts). Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the @peas{120%g} and heat until piping hot, ~{1%minute}.

Mix in the @butter{20%g} until melted.

Stir in the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g}, then taste the sauce and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Once ready, stir through the cooked spaghetti. Add a splash of @water{} to loosen the sauce if needed.

Share the prawn spaghetti between your #bowls{}.

Sprinkle over the @chilli flakes{1%pinch} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) to finish. Enjoy!